=====Panama=====
{{Main|Women in Panama}}
'''Women in Panama''' are the women who live in or are from [[Panama]]. Panamanian women, by tradition, are [[Hispanic]] and they are treated as equal to men, accorded with "deference and respect". Young women in Panama, particularly those who are single, are regarded as persons with "very high symbolic status", including giving them roles as "[[Carnaval Queen]]s". One particular example of this type of reverence of female adolescents is the celebration of the ''[[inna suid]]'' by the [[Kuna Indian]]s, which is a three-day celebration of the adolescent girls' "[[coming of age]]". Some Panamanian women occupy high positions in the field of the professions, education, and government service. Panama had a female [[List of heads of state of Panama|president]] as their national leader, in the person of [[Mireya Moscoso]], who was Panama's first female president, serving from 1999 to 2004. <ref name=EC>[http://www.everyculture.com/No-Sa/Panama.html Panama], everyculture.com</ref>

==South America==
Women from [[South America]] include women who reside in [[Women in Argentina|Argentina]], [[Women in Bolivia|Bolivia]], [[Women in Brazil|Brazil]], [[Women in Chile|Chile]], [[Women in Colombia|Colombia]], [[Women in Ecuador|Ecuador]], [[Women in Guyana|Guyana]], [[Women in Paraguay|Paraguay]], [[Women in Peru|Peru]], [[Women in Suriname|Suriname]], [[Women in Trinidad and Tobago|Trinidad and Tobago]], [[Women in Uruguay|Uruguay]], and [[Women in Venezuela|Venezuela]].

===Argentina===
{{Main|Women in Argentina}}
'''Women in Argentina''' have attained a relatively high level of equality by [[Latin America]]n standards, and in the [[Global Gender Gap Report]] prepared by the [[World Economic Forum]] in 2009, Argentine women ranked 24th among 134 countries studied in terms of their access to resources and opportunities relative to men.<ref>[http://www.lanacion.cl/mujeres-siguen-siendo-discriminadas/noticias/2009-10-27/203100.html ''La Naci<U+00F3>n'': Mujeres siguen siendo discriminadas {{es}}]</ref> They enjoy comparable levels of [[Education in Argentina|education]], and somewhat higher [[Gross enrollment ratio|school enrollment ratios]] than their male counterparts. They are well integrated in the nation's cultural and intellectual life,<ref>[http://portal.educ.ar/debates/eid/webcreatividad/publicaciones/la-mujer-y-sus-derechos.php Educ.ar: La mujer y sus derechos {{es}}]</ref> though less so in the nation's economy. Their economic clout in relation to men is higher than in most Latin American countries, however,<ref>[http://www.ieco.clarin.com/economia/Brecha-mujer-gana_0_82500032.html ''iEco'': Brecha salarial {{es}}]</ref> and numerous Argentine women hold top posts in the Argentine corporate world;<ref>[http://www.ieco.clarin.com/empresas/mujeres-manejan-millones_0_107700028.html ''iEco'': Las mujeres que manejan los millones {{es}}]</ref> among the best known are [[Cris Morena]], owner of the television production company by the same name, [[Mar<U+00ED>a Amalia Lacroze de Fortabat]], former CEO and majority stakeholder of [[Loma Negra]], the nation's largest cement manufacturer, and [[Ernestina Herrera de Noble]], director of [[Grupo Clar<U+00ED>n]], the premier media group in Argentina. 

===Bolivia===
{{Main|Women in Bolivia}}
'''Women in Bolivia''' face struggles in healthcare and cultural change, living in a country that is traditionally [[misogynist]], although the [[Constitution of Bolivia|constitution]] guarantees [[Women's rights|equal rights]] for women and men. Economically and politically, women have recently garnered more influence in decision making.  According to the [[Human Development Report]] Office of the [[United Nations Development Programme]], in Bolivia "men receive more and better education than women, receive increased and better health assistance than women, and have the possibility to generate greater income while working less...if we consider that women, as opposed to men, also have...the almost exclusive responsibility for domestic work".<ref name=UNICEF1/> [[Maternal mortality]] and [[illiteracy]] among women rate as some of the highest in the world.<ref name=UNICEF1>{{cite web|last=|first=|title=The Situation of Women in Bolivia|url=http://www.unicef.org/bolivia/children_1538.htm|work=[[UNICEF]]|accessdate=25 February 2012|date=}}</ref><ref name=SIG>{{cite web|last=|first=|title=Gender equality and social institutions in Bolivia|url=http://genderindex.org/country/bolivia|work=Social Institutions and Gender Index|accessdate=26 February 2012|date=}}</ref> Bolivian women are also exposed to excessive [[machismo]], being utilized as promotional tools in popular advertising which solidifies stereotypes and assumptions about women.<ref name="Walter2001H">{{cite book|author=Lynn Walter|title=Women's rights: a global view|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=P0IXyvEGao8C&pg=PA17|accessdate=26 February 2012|year=2001|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-30890-1|page=24}}</ref>

===Brazil===
{{Main|Women in Brazil}}
Women in [[Brazil]] enjoy the same legal rights and duties as men, what is clearly expressed in the 5th article of Brazil's 1988 Constitution.<ref>http://www.loc.gov/law/help/guide/nations/brazil.php</ref> A cabinet-level office, the Secretariat for Women's Affairs, oversees a special secretariat that has responsibility to ensure the legal rights of women. Although the law prohibits discrimination based on gender in employment and wages, there were significant wage disparities between men and women.  However, many women have been elected mayors and many women have been federal judges.  The first female assumed office in the [[Senate of Brazil|Senate]] in 1979.  Women became candidates for vice president for the first time in 1994. As of 2009, only 9%  of the seats in the national parliament were held by women.<ref>http://data.un.org/CountryProfile.aspx?crname=Brazil</ref>

===Chile===
{{Main|Women in Chile}}
The lives, roles, and rights of '''women in Chile''' have gone through many changes over time. Chilean women's societal roles have historically been impacted by traditional [[gender roles]] and a [[patriarchy|patriarchal culture]],<ref name=Menkedick2010>{{cite web|last=Menkedick|first=Sarah|title=Machismo in Chile: Serious Barrier to Gender Equality|url=http://news.change.org/stories/machismo-in-chile-serious-barrier-to-gender-equality|work=Change.org|accessdate=24 February 2012|date=23 May 2010}}</ref> but throughout the twentieth century, women increasingly involved themselves in [[politics]] and [[protest]], resulting in provisions to the [[constitution]] to uphold equality between men and women and prohibit [[Sexism|sex discrimination]].

Women's educational attainment, workforce participation, and rights have improved, especially since [[Chile]] became a [[democracy]] again in 1990. Chile legalized [[divorce]] in 2004 and is also one of the few countries to have elected a [[Michelle Bachelet|female president]].<ref name=SIGI>{{cite web|title=Gender Equality and Social Institutions in Chile|url=http://genderindex.org/country/chile|publisher=Social Institutions and Gender Index|accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref>  However, Chilean women still face many economic and political challenges, including [[economic inequality|income disparity]], high rates of [[domestic violence]], and lingering gender roles.<ref name="Menkedick2010"/>

===Colombia===
{{Main|Women in Colombia}}
As established in the [[Colombian Constitution of 1991]], '''women in [[Colombia]]''' have the right to bodily integrity and autonomy; to vote (''see also: [[Elections in Colombia]]''); to hold public office; to work; to fair wages or equal pay; to own property; to receive an education; to serve in the military in certain duties, but are excluded from combat arms units; to enter into legal contracts; and to have marital, parental and religious rights. Women's rights in Colombia have been gradually developing since the early 20th Century.<ref>[http://webs.uvigo.es/pmayobre/textos/margarita_pelaez/voto_colombianas.doc {{es icon}} University of Vigo; political rights and citizenship of Colombian women]</ref>

