===Paraguay===
{{Main|Women in Paraguay}}
'''Women in Paraguay''' live in a culture that has been undergoing rapid change in recent decades. Women's rights were expanded through constitutional and legal changes during the 1990s. Cultural attitudes towards many areas of women's lives are also changing. Yet [[Paraguay]]an women still face many challenges in trying to attain social equality.

The legal and government institutions that currently exist in Paraguay were developed in part through the efforts of feminist organizations in the country that held significant awareness-raising campaigns during the 1990s to formalize the guarantees of women's rights.<ref>{{cite web|title=Social Institutions and Gender Index|url=http://genderindex.org/country/paraguay|publisher=http://genderindex.org|accessdate=September 4, 2011}}</ref>

The 1992 Constitution of Paraguay upholds the principle of equality for all individuals and prohibits discrimination.  However, socio-cultural practises still support discrimination against women in some areas.

===Peru===
{{Main|Women in Peru}}
'''Women in Peru''' represent a minority in both numbers and legal rights. Although historically somewhat equal to men, after the Spanish conquest the culture in what is now Peru became increasingly [[patriarchy|patriarchal]]. The patriarchal culture is still noticeable. Women receive less pay than men, have fewer employment and political opportunities, and are at times abused without repercussion. [[Contraceptive]] availability is not enough for the demand, and over a third of pregnancies end in [[abortion]]. Maternal death rates are also some of the highest in South America.

The [[Government of Peru|Peruvian Government]] has begun efforts to combat the high maternal mortality rate and lack of female political representation, as well as [[violence against women]]. However, the efforts have not yet borne fruit.

===Suriname===
{{Main|Women in Suriname}}
'''Women in Suriname''' are women who were born in, live in, or are from [[Suriname]]. [[Surinamese people|Surinamese]] women may be ethnically [[Indo-Surinamese|Hindustani]] (Hindostani), , [[Multiracial|Mixed]], [[Surinamese Creole people|Creole]]/[[Afro-Surinamese]], [[Javanese people|Javanese]], [[Maroon (people)|Maroon]], [[Amerindian]], or of other ancestry. Many women of Suriname work in the informal sector and in subsistence agriculture.<ref name=EC>[http://www.everyculture.com/Sa-Th/Suriname.html Suriname], everyculture.com</ref>

===Trinidad and Tobago===
{{Main|Women in Trinidad and Tobago}}
'''Women in Trinidad and Tobago''' are women who were born in, who live in, or are from [[Trinidad and Tobago]]. Depending from which island the women came from, the women of Trinidad and Tobago may also be called '''Trinidadian women''' or '''Tobagonian women'''.<ref name=EC/> Some women in Trinidad and Tobago now excel in occupations such as being microenterprise owners, "lawyers, judges, politicians, civil servants, journalists, and [[calypsonian]]s". Other women dominate in the fields of "domestic service, sales, and some light manufacturing".<ref name=EC/>

Women of Afro-Trinidadian mix commonly become "heads of households", thus with acquired "autonomy and power". By participating in Trinidad and Tobago's version of the [[Carnival]], Trinidadian and Tobagonian women demonstrate their "assertive sexuality". Some of them have also been active in so-called Afro-Christian sects and in running the "sou-sou informal rotating credit associations".<ref name=EC/>

===Uruguay===
{{Main|Women in Uruguay}}
'''Women in Uruguay''' are women who were born in, who live in, and are from [[Uruguay]]. According to ''Countries and Their Cultures'', there is a "very high proportion" of [[Uruguayan people|Uruguayan]] women participating in the labor force of the [[South America]]n country. And that [[Constitution of Uruguay|Uruguayan legislation]] maintains that the women of Uruguay have equal rights to power, authority, and privileges". In reality however women are still not occupying "higher economic, [[Education in Uruguay|professional]], [[Politics of Uruguay|political]], [[Demographics of Uruguay|social]], and [[Religion in Uruguay|religious]] positions".<ref name=EC>[http://www.everyculture.com/To-Z/Uruguay.html#b Division of Labor by Gender], Gender Roles and Statuses, Uruguay, everyculture.com</ref> In relation to the [[Politics of Uruguay|political arena]], [[UN Women]] reported that a 2012 study made by the [[Inter-Parliamentary Union]] (IPU) ranked Uruguay as being "103rd out of 189 countries in terms of [[Women in government|representation of women]] in [[General Assembly of Uruguay|Parliament]]" and that "only 12 per cent of the current members of the [[Senate of Uruguay|Chamber of Senators]] and [[Chamber of Deputies of Uruguay|Chamber of Deputies]] in Uruguay are women".<ref name=UNW>[http://www.unwomen.org/2013/01/young-uruguayan-women-aim-to-boost-their-role-in-politics/ Young Uruguayan women aim to boost their role in politics], [[UN Women]], January 29, 2013</ref>

